			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>San Francisco</placeName> <date>Nov. 24. 1854</date></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Dear Friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">I am much obliged<lb/> to you for the flattering notice&#44; with which you have<lb/> returned your thanks to me in your last Number of the<lb/> Occident&#44; and also the attention you have paid to<lb/> my report of Laying the Corner Stone of the Con&#45;<lb/>&#45;gregation.  I have heard many expressions of<lb/> admiration for your own notice or <del>preparatory</del> introductory<lb/> remarks of the Laying the Corner Stone&#44; but also regret<lb/> that many did not get their Occidents.</p>
				<p>Your <placeName>Marysville</placeName> subscribers tell me&#44; that they have<lb/> paid <persName>Mayer</persName> their dues&#59; <persName>Mr. F. M. Reinhart</persName> of<lb/> <placeName>Marysville</placeName> has paid me &#36;3&#8212; though he had<lb/> paid it to <persName>Mayer</persName>&#59; he requests me to inform you<lb/> that he desires to discontinue his subscription.<lb/>  <persName>Messrs. B. Kohn</persName>&#44; <persName>Stein Eisner &#38; Co</persName>&#44; <persName>Lehman &#38; Co</persName> &#38;<lb/> <persName>Genson</persName>&#44; have left their places of Residence&#44; and<lb/> if you do continue to send them the Occident&#44; you<lb/> will never&#44; I do not believe receive any dues form them.<lb/>  <persName>Mr I &#38; J Labbat</persName> has told me&#44; that he has sent<lb/> you the money for the Bible&#44; which he has received<lb/> from you.  I have delivered the sunday school<lb/> Books&#44; but was unable as yet to get the money&#44;<lb/> but I have the promise of <persName>H. Seligman</persName> soon to re&#45;</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>ceive it.  On the <date>22d</date> inst. the Eureka Benevolent<lb/> Society gave a Ball&#44; which was well conducted&#59; the so&#45;<lb/>&#45;ciety have cleared by it about &#36;1000&#59; they are in<lb/> a very prosperous condition and have 120 members.<lb/>  Send an Occident and some Back Numbers to<lb/> <persName>Mr. Cohn</persName> care of <persName>Barnett Keesing</persName> <placeName>Box 488 San Francisco</placeName><lb/> whose subscription I got.</p>
				<p>In about 3 months I shall&#44; please God&#44; be in<lb/> <placeName>Phila.</placeName>&#44; before my Departure I hope to be able<lb/> to send you some money&#59; it is harder to<lb/> get trifling amounts generally speaking&#44; due you<lb/> than it is in the states.  <persName>Mr. Steppacher</persName> might<lb/> perhaps suit you the best as the man you have re<lb/>&#45;marked in your last Letter you would desire for<lb/> selling your works&#44; as he is shamos for the<lb/> Congregation Emanu&#45;El&#59; I have spoken upon that<lb/> subject to him&#44; and he tells me&#44; he would be<lb/> willing to make some arrangements with you.</p>
				<p><persName>Mr. &#38; J. Labbat</persName> has informed me that he has<lb/> transmitted to you the Result of the<lb/> Election&#44; which has taken place some 6 weeks ago&#44;<lb/> in which you have perceived that <persName>Dr. Eckman</persName> was<lb/> taken up by the Congregation at &#36;2000 salary for<lb/> one year&#59; he has now his school regularly<lb/> established for the Instruction of the children<lb/> in Hebrew&#44; who make admirable progress<lb/> in their studies&#59; he gives 3 times in the week<lb/> Lessons&#44; besides the sunday school&#44; which is<lb/> under his superintendence&#59; 40 children attend now</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>In conclusion let me extend you my best<lb/> wishes for your Prosperity</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Whilst I remain In Haste</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Yours Truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Cauffman &#38; Meyers</persName></p>
				<p><persName>Mr &#38; Mrs Roggenburger</persName></p>
				<p>desire their kind Regards</p>
				<p>to you</p>
			
